>>13368816
>I think his point was more along the lines of there being a quantity rush, and this having developed an expectation of very regular releases regardless of quality.
I don't doubt there are writers here who try to churn out frequent updates either to keep themselves on the OP list or just because they want to, but it's not necessarily a bad thing. I'm not sure how many writefags here have deeper aspirations in writing, but pretty much ANY writing professor or published author will tell you to practice every day if you can. It's just like any other craft or talent; you get better by practicing, simple as that. A place like /hmofa/ is the best kind of format to get immediate, unfiltered feedback on your work, rather than finishing a whole story and then sending it off to some editor/proofreader who might just toss it off to the side anyway.

I think the ONLY point our grumpy anon friend made is that sometimes the blogging gets a little excessive. We had this issue a few months back when threads would barely last more than half a day because of real-life discussion derailments, but as soon as it was brought up as a grievance everyone dialed it back and things were peachy once more. Yeah, it's been happening again a little bit recently, but on the other hand that's also because a lot of writers have things going on in their lives that are flat out stopping them from posting greens for a while. Keeping everyone in the loop will prevent more threadly "Where is X?" posts that have happened to several of our writers who are still MIA.

Anonymous Sat 06 Jan 2018 19:34:12 No.13370201 Report
Quoted By: >>13370286 >>13372266
>>13370109
You might be overthinking things, not to sound negative. If you’re doing a fight scene for example, you don’t need to clarify what everyone’s foot position is like or how they’re holding their weapon, UNLESS it’s important to the scene. Focus on the key elements you’re trying to illustrate and let the readers fill in the blanks for you. It also depends on the “speed” of the moment. If the action flies by, imitate it with short, quick descriptions. If a character is trudging along slowly, you can get more descriptive to reflect how sluggishly everything is moving. Control the speed of the reader with how fast you think action’s going, if that makes sense.

Anonymous Sun 07 Jan 2018 01:38:11 No.13375066 Report

>>13374458
Try reading some lines out loud. If you actively paused in certain portions, then you should add a comma.
>But if they were waiting for you, then this elevator could be your coffin
>"Wait i can pa-" you fire two bursts into his chest, cutting of his words
Like that.

As for writing more human dialogue, read more non-fiction and get a grip on how to write meaningful interaction as well as characters with flaws. I'm not referring to the same flaws as Anon's lack of augments because from what I've read you've completely negated that flaw by making him a perfect fighter, having such excellent aim in an environment where others with potential precision-aiding augments are being outdone by him
.
That's not to say that characters can't be strong, but powerful characters needs traits that keep them from being an unstoppable killing machine. An example would be like this: Character A is an amazing marksman, who feels more natural when a gun is in his hand and is capable of being perfectly calm in the middle of a gunfight and shoot without distractions. However, he lacks diplomacy skills and is terrible at making decisions on his own, leading to him making mistakes and letting targets escape often. This is where Character B comes in, who is a confident speaker, great at negotiation and quick thinking, but is completely average in every other aspect. These two character can work together and make up for where the other lacks and creates better relationships from just two characters doing contracts together because...they do.

Notice how Character A is now given a goal-to become more independent and be able to function properly when Character B isn't there to back him up. This is good character development, so make sure to incorporate it into plot events and not just mention it every once in a while without doing anything.

If you find writing hard, that's because it is hard. Like drawing, it's a skill you have to improve consciously.
